# <span style="color:rgb(140, 43, 29)">Pressure from Particles: A Simple Gas Model</span>

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
# <span style="color:rgb(140, 43, 29)">Pressure from Particles: A Simple Gas Model</span>

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
What does a pressure sensor actually measure?

At the microscopic level, a gas does not push on a wall continuously. Instead, the wall receives a rapid sequence of tiny impacts from many moving molecules. Each collision transfers a small amount of momentum. When many of these impulses are averaged over time, they appear as a smooth macroscopic pressure.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
What does a pressure sensor actually measure?

At the microscopic level, a gas does not push on a wall continuously. Instead, the wall receives a rapid sequence of tiny impacts from many moving molecules. Each collision transfers a small amount of momentum. When many of these impulses are averaged over time, they appear as a smooth macroscopic pressure.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
In this notebook, we build a simple two-dimensional toy model of that idea. A collection of particles moves inside a square container, bounces elastically from the walls, and the simulation counts how often those wall collisions happen.

The model is deliberately simple: particles do not collide with one another, and the temperature is represented by the step size of their motion. Even with these simplifications, the simulation is enough to show how a macroscopic pressure-like signal can emerge from many microscopic impacts.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
In this notebook, we build a simple two-dimensional toy model of that idea. A collection of particles moves inside a square container, bounces elastically from the walls, and the simulation counts how often those wall collisions happen.

The model is deliberately simple: particles do not collide with one another, and the temperature is represented by the step size of their motion. Even with these simplifications, the simulation is enough to show how a macroscopic pressure-like signal can emerge from many microscopic impacts.

