%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
Here we use a two-dimensional analogy. Since the walls are line segments rather than surfaces, the pressure-like quantity is proportional to force per unit length:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Here we use a two-dimensional analogy. Since the walls are line segments rather than surfaces, the pressure-like quantity is proportional to force per unit length:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
 $P_{\mathrm{2D}} \sim \frac{F}{L}$,

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
 $P_{\mathrm{2D}} \sim \frac{F}{L}$,

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
where  $L$  is the length of the wall. The value plotted in this simulation should therefore be read as a normalized pressure signal, not as pressure in physical units such as pascals.

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
